    # game/traveling.rpy:245
    old "You take a short ride through the roads surrounding the tower. The branches, rocks, plants, and bones are cleared, the trail evened-out, and in many spots you notice large prints left by the boulder-like feet. {color=#f6d6bd}Eudocia{/color} has kept her word. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:245
    old "Crossing these hills should be much easier now."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:255
    old "As you descend, you think of {color=#f6d6bd}Aeli’s{/color} reaction to the bronze rod. You {i}could{/i} ignore him and take a few minutes to tie it to one of the ledges, just nearby. This place is already high above the woodlands. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:255
    old "Just in case, I look behind, then get on the ground."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:255
    old "This is the monks’ land, and I should obey their laws. I ride ahead."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:255
    old "This may not be {i}my{/i} order, but I ought to obey the monks’ laws. I ride ahead."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:283
    old "You seek a spot that isn’t too easily seen from the trail, then make sure it won’t crumble under your weight. After a few minutes, you finish placing the rod - held by a cord and a few heavy rocks. You doubt anyone would stumble upon it. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:306
    old "You ride by a patrol from {color=#f6d6bd}Creeks{/color} that’s escorting a cart loaded with timber. They greet you politely, mentioning the growing safety on the roads. As you ride further, you notice the fresh coat of pebbles covering the muddier scraps of the trail, the trimmed shrubs, and the cleared tufts of grass. \n\nFrom now on, it should be easier to cross the path between {color=#f6d6bd}Foggy Lake{/color} and the village. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:306
    old "Finally, the locals are waking up."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:306
    old "I’m making a difference."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:321
    old "The road downhill meanders, slowing you down and forcing you to pay close attention not only to the shadows of the trees, but also to the tight, rocky passages. You can’t help but notice a few caves and fine ambush spots. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:321
    old "I keep an eye out for any sign of life."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:331
    old "{color=#f6d6bd}[horsename]{/color} trots with ease, unbothered by the few branches covering the beaten road. The bird songs and distant howls draw your attention to the forest, which gets sparser and brighter. You spot boars, roe deer, and saurians. \n\nThe sight of a nearby wolf pack worries you, but once you push your hips forward and your palfrey enters a canter, the beasts don’t even begin a pursuit. The speed alone will protect you from many dangers. \n\nYou notice a stone tower, taller than the trees. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:331
    old "It must be the inn I’ve heard about."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:344
    old "The road uphill meanders, slowing you down and forcing you to pay close attention not only to the shadows of the trees, but also to the tight, rocky passages. You can’t help but notice a few caves and fine ambush spots. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:357
    old "You slow down. Among the shrubs, a small pack of dragonlings is feasting on the carcass of a gray auroch. One of them, with red feathers on its arms, straightens up, and gives you a curious glance. Its head tilts left and right, forward and back. It screeches at you, but doesn’t move forward, and returns to its meal. \n\nYou wonder what would happen if you were on foot. Would they let you be, satisfied with their prey? Or would they run after you? But if so - for what reason? For now, you have enough space to move forward, yet stay safe. \n\nThe powerful jaws break the monster’s bones loudly, then bite off and swallow chunks of meat. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:357
    old "I keep my distance and look over my shoulder."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:369
    old "You enter the wetlands, with their many streams, ponds, and fish. Large birds run and fly between the gray, sparse trees that are covered with moss, mushrooms, and critters. For a human, it may be an unwelcoming and harsh realm, but the overwhelming swarms of insects prove that it’s a realm full of life. \n\nThe danger, with teeth and claws, is hidden below the water’s surface. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:369
    old "I stay away from the banks."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:381
    old "The shapes of mountains are cutting through the horizon. The water gets gradually less muddy. The cleaner it gets, the more animals you see. \n\nA family of deer blocks the road, resting and enjoying the cold water, which would be deadly for a human stomach. You consider riding around them, through the sparse meadow, but your presence also causes them disquiet. Without much haste, they regroup and run east, into the leafy forest. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:381
    old "I travel forward."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:395
    old "The family of deer you met some days ago has returned to the pond, this time accompanied by more members of their pack. One buck towers over all the others, with antlers as large as your palfrey. It takes a few steps toward you, shaking its head - {i}you better stay where you are{/i}. \n\nYou observe their curious, lazy glances. While the adults quench their thirst, the young ones are playing in the tall grasses, or basking in the middle of the road. \n\nIt takes quite a few minutes before the large beast orders the others to head back into the woods. Its bellow is like a falling boulder. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:395
    old "I wait for a few minutes patiently."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:395
    old "Stupid beasts."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:414
    old "For the first hour, the elder swings his staff around, like a conjurer in the marketplace, and hums to himself like a drunkard. His walking pace remains stable. \n\nAs time goes on, this frenzied state fades out. At first, he returns to using his staff, then gives you his bag. He looks down, hobbling, and finally asks you for help. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:414
    old "I get him in the saddle."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:427
    old "I ride forward, but I keep my distance and look over my shoulder."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:440
    old "A group of wolves chases after you, but the road is beaten and free of litter, and serves your palfrey well. You notice paths between the fruit-bearing trees on your right, and soon after that, you ride alongside vast fields of green hemp plants, taller than you are, waiting for a scythe or sickle. Then there are broad beans, much shorter, but healthy, almost ready for the second harvest of the summer. \n\nThe path ends with a massive wooden gate. The stone wall, separating you from the glow of lights behind it, isn’t as tall as the roofs, but you can’t imagine climbing to its top. There are pretty much no cracks, no missing bricks, a sign of many hours of labor, especially considering how massive the settlement is, as wide as a city district. \n\nThe birds and monkeys are now just a distant echo, while the beasts that were pursuing you stay in place, too afraid to get any closer. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:440
    old "I ride forward, ignoring my wounds, before they resume the pursuit."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:440
    old "*sigh* Let’s get this over with."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:456
    old "The road is beaten and free of litter, and serves your palfrey well. You notice paths between the fruit-bearing trees on your right, and soon after that, you ride alongside vast fields of green hemp plants, taller than you are, waiting for a scythe or sickle. Then there are broad beans, much shorter, but healthy, almost ready for the second harvest of the summer. \n\nThe path ends with a massive wooden gate. The stone wall, separating you from the glow of lights behind it, isn’t as tall as the roofs, but you can’t imagine climbing to its top. There are pretty much no cracks, no missing bricks, a sign of many hours of labor, especially considering how massive the settlement is, as wide as a city district. \n\nThe birds and monkeys are now just a distant echo, replaced with the sounds of carts, running, hammers, saws, laughter, and shouts. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:473
    old "You pass bootprints, cart tracks, pieces of rubbish, a long log used by wayfarers to sit down and rest. The trees grow sparsely, the path is well-lit, and the creatures you hear are either small or far away. The grass isn’t high enough to provide cover for massive cats. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:473
    old "I can ride in peace for once."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:484
    old "The road is beaten and free of litter. You notice paths between the fruit-bearing trees on your right, and soon after that, you ride alongside vast fields of broad beans, almost ready for the second harvest of the summer. Then there are the green hemp plants, taller than you are, waiting for a scythe or sickle. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:484
    old "The locals keep the beasts at a distance, I guess."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:494
    old "You pass bootprints, cart tracks, pieces of rubbish, and the old signs of maintenance, from cut shrubs to stones pushed to the side. The monkeys and birds are small, and the hills turn greener the farther west you get. The sound of a distant creek is relaxingly monotonous. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:494
    old "It looks like I can ride in peace for once."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:504
    old "You pass bootprints, cart tracks, pieces of rubbish, cut shrubs, moved stones, and trees felled with tools. The forest on your left and right is thick, but not too dark. The monkeys and birds you spot are small, and the larger, foraging creatures also keep their distance. The sound of a distant river is relaxingly monotonous. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:520
    old "The man stops near the clearing and leans on his staff, contemplating the clearing silently. \n\n“When I was but a brat, ne a bough was trimmed without a greater purpose. Ne only for humans, both for the trees en land. Pinching the spirits was a misdeed.” \n\nHe turns to you, observing your lips. “I’ve heard tales of great sages, from before the days of the emperors, who restored such lands with a single spell, brought them back to life. Helped us find forgiveness, the right path.” "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:520
    old "“And where are these sages now?”"
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:527
    old "“Those are just stories,” he glances at the dead trees. “Made up by those who dream of salvation, but do ne know what they need to be saved from. Who think there’s a balm that will cure a soul, the fate itself.” \n\nHe resumes his walk. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:543
    old "You ascend a gentle hill, with green thickets coating the valleys. The path is like an endless bridge built by the ancient three-legged giants, or maybe by the pagan spellcasters. \n\nThe higher you get, the fewer plants you see. Hit by a cold wind, you adjust your cloak. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:543
    old "I ride slowly, sitting in the center of the saddle. Mountains are harsh for horses."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:555
    old "The curvy road east is overgrown. {color=#f6d6bd}[horsename]{/color} trots when it has a chance, but more often it walks, forced to jump over larger branches blocking the path. The nearby lake is surrounded by thirsty wildlife. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:555
    old "I observe the dark forest, ready to react if something jumps at me."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:578
    old "Before I ride further away, I spend an hour or so clearing the path."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:578
    old "I’m too tired to clear the path. (Required vitality: 2) (disabled)"
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:588
    old "Turns out a few of the plants were already dried-out, and are not too heavy. You get a bit sweaty, but unless another misfortune happens, the path should stay in pretty good shape. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:588
    old "I get back in the saddle."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:630
    old "As long as you ride uphill, the forest is sparse. Soon after, the tree roots tear the path apart. The road is coated with branches, acorns, leaves, and chestnuts, and some seedlings have already broken through the pitted surface of the road. If left undisturbed for another year or two, the forest will reclaim this place. \n\nFinally, you ride upward again. The plants are getting smaller, the road more rocky. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:630
    old "I sigh with relief."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:641
    old "It wouldn’t be wise to ride through a lush meadow. There are animal pits and molehills, and the ground is covered with old roots, rocks, and mounds. Putting more weight on {color=#f6d6bd}[horsename]{/color} could turn any stumble into a broken leg. \n\nYou lead it by the reins, and keep looking around - such lands are a common hunting ground for dragonlings, or cats that sneak in the grass. \n\nFinally, you reach a narrow game trail. The rest of the journey should be easier. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:641
    old "Let’s follow it."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:656
    old "The first part of the trail is narrow and overgrown. The steep crag in the south divides the lush forest in half. You barely recognize any shapes in the entanglement of grays, browns, and greens. \n\nThe northern landscape, while similarly impenetrable, is the exact opposite. The meadow turns into barren hills and mountains, barely covered by grass and bushes. Maybe the riding ibexes of the clanspeople from The Growing Mountains would get through such a barrier. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:656
    old "There are no clans here."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:673
    old "You prepare for another chase, seeing the first few members of the pack of spotted wolves, but this time, they only observe you. A few howls come from a place you can’t see, and the colorful animals turn away, vanishing into the leas. "
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:673
    old "They wasted enough time already."
    new ""

    # game/traveling.rpy:673
    old "They grew afraid of me."
    new ""

